21 (1 in 30). \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EShe is now considering if she wants to continue the pregnancy and she wishes to have further diagnostic testing to determine if the fetus will have Down syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic test to offer this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further investigation is suitable","Non-invasive Prenatal Testing (NIPT)","Chorionic villous sampling (CVS)","Amniocentesis","Morphology ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECombined First Trimester Screening (CFTS) is a government funded risk stratification tool for common chromosomal abnormalities (T13, T18 and T21), calculated using maternal serology markers (PAPP-A, b-hCG) and the nuchal translucency reported on ultrasound. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChorionic villous sampling (CVS)\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is the most appropriate next step for a patient with high risk FTS wishing to investigate the likelihood of Down syndrome. This will test for genetic or biochemical anomalies and if positive, could point towards Down syndrome. As with all invasive testing, care must be taken to appropriately counsel the patient regarding risks. CVS and amniocentesis both carry an approximate 0.35% risk of miscarriage.\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003EAmniocentesis\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Ewould be offered to the patient at 15 weeks of gestation or above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-invasive Prenatal Testing (NIPT) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a screening tool used in the first trimester that analyses fragments of fetal DNA in the maternal serology for evidence of chromosomal abnormalities. It is a screening test with low risk of false positives through detecting placental mosaicism, however has higher sensitivity than CFTS. The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists do recommend offering NIPT as a possible secondary screen for women with an increased probability of aneuploidy on primary screening. However, in this instance the patient wishes to have a definitive diagnosis to guide her decision about termination of her pregnancy so NIPT is not appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the patient was not wanting invasive testing and was not wanting to terminate the pregnancy then a \u003Cstrong\u003Emorphology ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0could be performed. This will often provide more information to further guide patient decision making but cannot provide a definitive diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing discussion of risks and benefits, the patient may elect for\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eno further investigation\u003C/strong\u003E. However, it is important to offer all available options to facilitate shared decision making with the patient.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First trimester screening provides risk stratification through maternal serum testing and ultrasound.","Invasive genetic testing such as chorionic villous sampling and amniocentesis carry a low risk of miscarriage.","Chorionic villous sampling is suitable for identifying chromosomal abnormalities in high risk first trimester pregnancies."],"references":["Kagan KO, Sonek J, Wagner P, Hoopmann M. Principles of first trimester screening in the age of non-invasive prenatal diagnosis: screening for chromosomal abnormalities. Arch Gynecol Obstet. 2017 Oct;296(4):645-651. doi: 10.1007/s00404-017-4459-9. Epub 2017 Jul 12. PMID: 28702698.","Beta J, Lesmes-Heredia C, Bedetti C, Akolekar R. Risk of miscarriage following amniocentesis and chorionic villus sampling: a systematic review of the literature. Minerva Ginecol. 2018;70(2):215-219. doi:10.23736/S0026-4784.17.04178-8","Prenatal screening and diagnostic testing for fetal chromosomal and genetic conditions. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists and Human Genetics Society of Australia. 2018. Available at: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Prenatal-Screening-and-Diagnostic-Testing-for-Fetal-Chromosomal-and-Genetic-Conditions.pdf","Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. \u201cPrenatal Testing.\u201d Racgp.org.au, 19 Dec. 2023, www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/genomics-in-general-practice/genetic-tests-and-technologies/prenatal-testing."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97435"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13038"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97435"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T17:34:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T17:35:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5475"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115432"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relat